# Purpose

Generate complete and production-ready Azure DevOps (ADO) User Stories following Agile best practices.

The generated user story must be ready for:
- Sprint Planning
- Backlog Refinement
- Development
- QA Test Case Design
- UAT Execution

Do not generate implementation details unless explicitly requested.

# User Story Structure

Always generate user stories using the following sections and order.

## User Story Number

If provided by the user, use it.

If not provided:

```
TBD
```

## Title

Format:

```
<Business Capability> - <Action>
```

Examples:

- Billing - Create Invoice Adjustment
- Contract Management - Amend Existing Contract
- Account Management - Update Customer Status

Title must be concise and business-focused.

## As a

Identify the persona.

Examples:

- Billing Specialist
- Sales Representative
- Contract Manager
- Operations User
- Customer Service Agent
- System

If persona is unclear, ask the user.

## I want to

Describe the goal from the user's perspective.

Format:

```
I want to <action>
```

Examples:

- I want to create invoice adjustments
- I want to update contract details
- I want to view customer billing history

## So That

Describe the business value.

Examples:

- So that billing records remain accurate.
- So that customer information is up to date.
- So that contract amendments are processed efficiently.

Must focus on business outcome.

## Description

Provide detailed business requirements.

Include:

- Current process
- Future process
- Functional expectations
- Business rules
- Dependencies
- Assumptions

Use bullet points where possible.

# Acceptance Criteria

Generate acceptance criteria in Gherkin format.

Use numbering.

Format:

### AC1

```gherkin
Given
When
Then
```

### AC2

```gherkin
Given
When
Then
```

Requirements:

- Every acceptance criterion must be testable.
- Avoid technical implementation details.
- Cover happy path.
- Cover validation scenarios.
- Cover error scenarios.
- Cover permission scenarios if applicable.

# Business Rules

Create separate section.

Format:

## Business Rules

BR1:
BR2:
BR3:

Examples:

- BR1: Only active customers can create invoices.
- BR2: Billing adjustments require manager approval.
- BR3: Contract end date cannot precede start date.

# Field Requirements

If fields are mentioned, generate a table.

| Field Name | Required | Type | Validation |
|------------|----------|------|------------|

# Object Impact Analysis

For Salesforce/Fusion projects always identify impacted objects.

Format:

## Objects Impacted

| Object | Action |
|----------|----------|
| Account | Update |
| Contract | Create |
| Invoice | Update |

Actions:

- Create
- Update
- Delete
- Read

# Security and Permissions

Identify affected personas and permissions.

Format:

| Persona | Create | Read | Update | Delete |
|----------|----------|----------|----------|----------|

# Dependencies

List:

- Upstream dependencies
- Downstream dependencies
- Integration dependencies
- Batch dependencies

# Assumptions

List assumptions separately.

# Out of Scope

Clearly identify items not included in the story.

# Testability Review

Before final output verify:

- Every requirement has acceptance criteria.
- Acceptance criteria are testable.
- Business rules are defined.
- Personas are identified.
- Object impacts are identified.
- Dependencies are documented.

# Output Format

Always generate in this exact sequence:

1. User Story Number
2. Title
3. As a
4. I want to
5. So That
6. Description
7. Acceptance Criteria
8. Business Rules
9. Field Requirements
10. Objects Impacted
11. Security and Permissions
12. Dependencies
13. Assumptions
14. Out of Scope
15. Testability Review

# Validation Rules

Do not generate the user story if any of the following are missing:

- Persona
- Business objective
- Expected outcome

Instead ask clarification questions.

# Salesforce/Fusion Specific Instructions

Whenever Salesforce/Fusion requirements are detected:

- Identify impacted standard objects.
- Identify impacted custom objects.
- Identify automation impacts.
- Identify batch process impacts.
- Identify integration impacts.
- Identify security model impacts.
- Identify reporting impacts.

# Quality Gate

A user story is considered complete only if:

- INVEST principle is satisfied.
- Acceptance criteria are testable.
- Business value is clear.
- No ambiguity exists.
- QA can derive test cases directly from the story.
- Development team can estimate effort without additional clarification.